pmc Sci Rep Sci Rep 1579 scirep Scientific Reports 2045-2322 Nature Publishing Group PMC12488896 PMC12488896.1 12488896 12488896 41034410 10.1038/s41598-025-15690-6 15690 1 Article Candidate serum metabolite biomarkers of subclinical Haemonchus contortus Jawad Hamza 1 Gellatly Desiree 2 Lei Yaogeng 2 Thompson Sean 2 Borzouei Shima 1 Osonowo Olufemi 1 Gilleard John S. 3 Miar Younes 1 Goldansaz Seyed Ali 2 4 Manafiazar Ghader manafiazar@dal.ca 1 1 https://ror.org/01e6qks80 grid.55602.34 0000 0004 1936 8200 Department of Animal Science and Aquaculture, Faculty of Agriculture, Dalhousie University, 2 https://ror.org/04rxjcv17 grid.423088.5 0000 0000 9197 8231 Technology Access Centre for Livestock Production, Olds College of Agriculture and Technology, 3 https://ror.org/03yjb2x39 grid.22072.35 0000 0004 1936 7697 Faculty of Veterinary Medicine, Host-Parasite Interactions Program, University of Calgary, 4 https://ror.org/05c5y5q11 grid.423814.8 0000 0000 9965 4151 Sustainable Livestock Systems Branch, Sustainable Agri-Food Sciences Division, Agri-Food and Biosciences Institute, 1 10 2025 2025 15 478255 34203 14 5 2025 11 8 2025 01 10 2025 03 10 2025 03 10 2025 © The Author(s) 2025 2025 https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/ Open Access http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/ Parasitic infection is a major factor negatively affecting sheep production worldwide. The gold standard, fecal egg count, identifies only clinical stages after egg count establishment and shedding in the feces. However, detection at the sub-clinical phase could offer a critical window for strategic deworming and prevent production losses. Blood metabolites often perform as signalling molecules preceding major physiological events; thus, they could provide a prognosis of immunological alterations in the host. Therefore, we conducted a controlled longitudinal study to identify predictive biomarkers of Haemonchus contortus p H. contortus Supplementary Information The online version contains supplementary material available at 10.1038/s41598-025-15690-6. Keywords Metabolomics Ewe lambs Anthelmintic resistance Predictive biomarker Early detection Fecal egg count Subject terms Metabolomics Predictive markers Animal physiology Parasite host response Parasite immune evasion pmc-status-qastatus 0 pmc-status-live yes pmc-status-embargo no pmc-status-released yes pmc-prop-open-access yes pmc-prop-olf no pmc-prop-manuscript no pmc-prop-legally-suppressed no pmc-prop-has-pdf yes pmc-prop-has-supplement yes pmc-prop-pdf-only no pmc-prop-suppress-copyright no pmc-prop-is-real-version no pmc-prop-is-scanned-article no pmc-prop-preprint no pmc-prop-in-epmc yes issue-copyright-statement © Springer Nature Limited 2025 Introduction Parasitic infections and building resistance to anthelmintic drugs are considered one of the major challenges facing sheep production around the globe, with Haemonchus contortus 1 Haemonchus contortus 2 4 H. contortus 5 5 6 7 8 9 10 The particular diagnostic challenge is that during the pre-patent period 5 H. contortus 11 12 13 14 15 16 18 As the parasites propagate, the clinical manifestation of the signs, depending on parasite load and host immunity, becomes visible and measurable at the phenotypic level with the highest FECs 2 6 19 20 21 22 Previous studies have shown that sheep parasites manipulate host metabolism at the molecular level 22 24 25 26 22 27 28 29 27 22 23 H. contortus Therefore, we constructed a longitudinal controlled experiment and manually infected ewe lambs with H. contortus H. contortus H. contortus Results Findings from this study are presented in two main areas. First, the parasitological findings demonstrate sub-clinical infection progression and deworming (drenching) efficacy, and the second section presents metabolomic findings. Parasitological findings The nemabiome sequencing analysis confirmed 100% H. contortus p 1 p Table 1 Fecal egg counts (FEC) in Haemonchus contortus FEC Day Control (CT) Inoculat