xamine other pre-patent timepoints (e.g., 10 or 14 dpi) to improve the predictive biomarker panel strength. The 21 dpi predictive panel captured the critical transition point when FEC detection begins, while the 28 dpi predictive model identified peak metabolic disruption during established sub-clinical infection. Indole acetic acid levels were significantly higher in CT animals on 7 dpi compared to IN animals, while by 28 dpi, IN animals showed higher levels than CT animals. As a prominent candidate biomarker on early timepoints, IAA provides insights into host-parasite-microbiota metabolic crosstalk during parasite infections 51 52 H. contortus 43 45 53 54 55 56 57 58 Lysophosphatidylcholines (LysoPC a C18:0 and LysoPC a C14:0) were significantly lower in the IN group compared to the CT group on 7 dpi and 21 dpi, respectively. These metabolites are key in cell signalling and epithelial membrane remodelling 41 Fasciola hepatica ( 23 H. contortus 15 59 60 PC aa C38:0 and PC ae C40:6 (ether phospholipid) were significantly elevated in the IN group compared to the CT group on 21 dpi and 28 dpi, respectively. These phosphatidylcholines maintain cell membrane integrity 61 62 63 42 63 22 64 H. contortus 65 66 H. contortus 49 67 H. contortus 68 69 46 48 The significant metabolites and their associated disrupted pathways in the pre-drench phase of our study primarily provide the knowledge foundation for developing innovative diagnostic tools, while also suggesting potential therapeutic research directions. Previous studies demonstrate that targeted supplementation with arginine, histidine, and cysteine enhances immunity against GIN infection 70 71 72 H. contortus 25 73 H. contortus Post-drench phase The metabolic response to deworming in healthy animals revealed unexpected complexities that might have important implications for routine deworming practices in healthy livestock. The CT-D versus CT-ND group demonstrated significant drug-induced metabolic perturbations by a dramatic shift from a maximum of 6 altered metabolites pre-drench to 16 at the post-drench phase. The post-drench phase introduced several new metabolites, indicating that anthelmintics trigger extensive metabolic pathways in healthy animals. Specifically, significant phospholipid changes suggest direct drug interactions with cellular membranes, potentially affecting membrane fluidity and cellular signalling cascades 74 75 76 In contrast, the metabolic response to anthelmintic treatment in infected sheep followed distinct trajectories by affecting a few metabolites that reflect targeted recovery mechanisms. Two key metabolites (acetyl-ornithine and kynurenine) appeared consistently elevated in the IN-D group compared to the IN-ND group. They were absent in CT-D versus CT-ND analysis, revealing recovery mechanisms specific to previously infected animals. Acetyl-ornithine may play a role in nitrogen metabolism and tissue regeneration, potentially helpful for the abomasum internal membranes and functional recovery 75 77 78 79 50 80 Spermidine was significantly lower in IN-D compared to IN-ND at 42 dpi, likely reflecting ongoing restoration of polyamine homeostasis following parasite elimination in IN-D animals. Polyamine pathways are critical in both parasite survival mechanisms and host inflammatory responses during parasitic infections 81 82 43 45 Potential biological role of candidate biomarkers for post-drench assessment Particularly revealing were the metabolic differences between CT-D and IN-D animals, which show that prior parasitic sub-clinical infection leaves lasting metabolic fingerprints after FEC clearance. Serotonin consistently differentiated between the CT-D and IN-D groups, aligning with Castello et al. 83 Toxoplasma gondii 82 The 35 dpi predictive panel showed a statistical tendency. The 35 dpi panel metabolites (methionine-sulfoxide and SM(OH) C14:1) were significantly lower in IN-D animals as compared to CT-D. Their presence suggests ongoing oxidative stress and abomasal membrane remodelling processes 59 84 85 86 87 88 49 49 H. contortus 89 The 57 dpi predictive panel, combining SM(OH) C14:1 and C4 (butyrylcarnitine), indicates that even after an extended recovery time, previously infected animals maintain some distinct metabolic signatures. Both SM(OH) C14:1 and C4 levels were lower in the IN-D group compared to the CT-D group. Butyrylcarnitine serves as a key indicator of altered fatty acid metabolism and energy utilization patterns 90 91 Future studies should include H. contortus Economic advantages of the metabolomics approach Parasitic infections significantly impact sheep farming profitability; for example, the European sheep industry’s annual losses due to parasitic infection are around €1.8 billion 92 93 94 95 96 97 98 Other existing diagnostic alternatives also underperform, especially for on-farm applications. The FAMACHA © 99 100 20 101 102 101 103 104 From a parasite-control standpoint, the primary value of an early-warning blood test lies in its ability to drive a truly TST programme instead of whole-flock treatment. By identifying infected lambs during pre-patent or early patent sub-clinical infection stages, producers can drench only those individuals that are genuinely required. Therefore, deliberately leaving the remainder of the healthy animals untreated to act as a refugia (unexposed to treatment) of drug-susceptible genotypes 105 106 Metabolomics-based, cost-effective, farm-based predictive diagnostic tools could have significant economic implications for the worldwide sheep industry. For Alberta’s 100,000-head sheep industry, with annual parasite control costs of CAD $638,000 (Ivomec®: $4.80/animal; Safe-Guard®: $1.58/animal), implementing metabolomics-based diagnostics could reduce anthelmintic use by 50%. This estimate is based on the principle that early detection enables timely, targeted deworming of only affected animals, resulting in lower overall drug usage. Additionally, early control will reduce parasite transmission within the flock, minimizing the need for whole-flock treatments. This strategic approach would result in approximately $319,000 in annual savings. Moreover, this early intervention approach could shorten time to market by 17 days 96 Future directions This study successfully identified three distinct serum candidate biomarker panels for the detection of pre-patent (7 dpi), transition to patency (21 dpi), and peak patent sub-clinical infection (28 dpi). Post-drench predictive biomarkers also effectively distinguished previously infected animals with parasites from healthy animals. While these initial results are promising, further validation is necessary before field-deployable point-of-care tests can be developed for detecting sub-clinical infections. Candidate biomarkers validation should be performed across different sheep breeds, commercial production environments, and varying intensities of infection. It is also necessary to inoculate different H. contortus 107 Materials and methods Experimental design and animal management All experimental procedures (Animal Use Protocol #064) were approved by the Animal Care and Use Committee, Olds College of Agriculture and Technology, Alberta, Canada, and the animals were cared for in accordance with the guidelines of the Canadian Council on Animal Care 108 Sixty Rideau Arcott ewe lambs were sourced from a commercial sheep ranch near Olds, Alberta (T0C 2N0) and transported 140 km to Olds College of Agriculture & Technology (T4H 1E5) at 4 to 5 months of age. All animals were randomly selected from this single source to ensure genetic and management consistency across experimental groups. Following an acclimatization period, the current study commenced when animals reached 6 to 7 months old (44.6 ± 6.08 kg BW), and at the end of the study, all animals were confirmed to be in good health and free from drug residues. Prior to initiating the current 57-day trial, all animals were individually checked for their health status through analyses of the fecal and blood samples. Evaluating fecal samples for FEC showed no strongyle ( H. contortus On day − 1 (one day prior to inoculation procedure), animals were randomly assigned to two equal treatment groups, each with two subgroups, following a 2 × 2 factorial design: 1) Control, healthy ewe-lambs (CT, n = 30) that did not receive any H. contortus H. contortus S2 This study was conducted longitudinally over a 57-day period. Baseline sampling (blood, fecal and body weight [BW]) was performed on day − 1 (one day prior to experiment initiation), followed by parasite inoculation on day 0. Blood and fecal samples were collected at seven timepoints, including − 1, 7, 21, 28, 35, and 42, as well as on 56 (fecal samples) and 57 (blood sampling) days post-inoculation (dpi). At each timepoint, blood was drawn prior to fecal collection. Animal health status was monitored throughout the study, and blood samples were also analyzed for complete blood cell count to monitor hematological parameters as indicators of infection, while BW was recorded at each sampling timepoint to assess growth performance impacts. On day 0, all animals were inoculated with their assigned treatment. The two infected groups (IN-D and IN-ND) were orally inoculated with 5,000 third-stage H. contortus H. contortus No other procedure (except blood and fecal sample collections) was done on the animals until 28 dpi, when the drenched groups (CT-D and IN-D) received an oral inoculation of 0.8 mg/mL of ivermectin (Ivomec® Boehringer Ingelheim Animal Health Canada Inc., Ontario, Canada) at 2.5 mL/10 kg of BW and 100 mg/mL of fenbendazole (Safe-Guard®, Merck & Co., Inc., New Jersey, USA) at 2.3 mL/45 kg of BW. The dose rate was calculated based on the labelling of the drugs, veterinary approval, and average BW taken on 21 and 28 dpi. Similarly, the non-drenched groups (CT-ND and IN-ND) received an equivalent volume of sham (distilled water), calculated using the same formula as the drug dose calculation. On 35 dpi, all sixty animals received toltrazuril (Baycox®, Elanco Canada Limited, Ontario, Canada) at a dosage of 1 mL/2.5 kg of BW to address high coccidia counts detected during routine FEC analyses. This treatment specifically targeted coccidia and had no impact on H. contortus To prevent cross-contamination, the four groups were housed in separate outdoor feedlot pens with no interaction between them throughout the trial. Each pen was equipped with wind protection, sun shelter, and wood shavings for bedding. All lambs had ad libitum access to water and feed. The diet consisted of a total mixed ration based on whole barley and a protein supplement (4:1 ratio), with wheat straw bales freely available in all pens. The mixed grain ration provided 16% crude protein and 4 Mcal/kg digestible energy (on a dry matter basis), with a total digestible nutrients value of 82%, supplemented with wheat straw to ensure adequate fibre intake. Sample collection and analytical methods Blood sampling and processing Blood samples were collected at the Olds College sheep handling area by jugular venipuncture using 10-mL vacutainer tubes without anticoagulant. Blood samples remained at room temperature on site for approximately 30 min before being processed in batches of 16 animals in the centrifuge (2000 RPM, 4 °C) to collect the supernatant serum in 2-mL Eppendorf tubes. Eppendorf tubes were immediately placed in an insulated box with dry ice and then transferred to a − 20 °C freezer. Upon trial completion, 420 serum samples (60 animals, 7 samples each) were packaged in an insulated container with sufficient dry ice and transported to The Metabolomics Innovation Centre (TMIC) at the University of Alberta (approximately a two-hour drive), where they were received intact and stored at -80 °C until further analysis. Fecal sampling and parasitological analysis Immediately after blood collection, each time fecal samples (~ 10 g) were directly taken from the rectum of each sheep using disposable gloves, and the gloves were transferred to labelled Ziplock bags. Samples were stored in a cooler with ice packs and transported to a refrigerator (4 °C) on the same day of data collection. Within 7 days after collection, FEC analysis was performed using the modified McMaster technique 109 Haemonchus contortus 109 Parasite species identification was performed through nemabiome sequencing by Dr. John Gilleard’s laboratory (University of Calgary). Strategically, we selected samples from 42 and 56 dpi from the IN-ND group (n = 15) as these represented optimal timepoints with established chronic infection and sufficient egg counts for comprehensive analysis. All 15 samples were homogenized for both timepoints, and two representative samples were taken. These two pooled samples were shipped in air-evacuated Ziplock bags at room temperature. As per Avramenko et al. 110 110 Metabolomics analysis The serum samples were analyzed using DI/LC–MS/MS custom assay to identify and quantify up to 110 endogenous metabolites, including amino acids, acylcarnitines, biogenic amines, glycerophospholipids, sphingolipids, and sugars 111 Statistical analysis Analysis strategy A total of 87 statistical comparisons across the metabolomics dataset were conducted. The analysis strategy was structured into three main categories. First, blood metabolome kinetics were examined by conducting 36 within-group comparisons to track longitudinal changes across CT-ND, CT-D, IN-ND, IN-D, CT, and IN. These included biologically relevant pairings in pre-drench phase such as dpi (− 1 vs. 7), (− 1 vs. 21), (− 1 vs. 28), (7 vs. 21), (7 vs. 28), (21 vs. 28), and post-drench phase intervals (35 vs. 42), (35 vs. 57), (42 vs. 57). Second, 30 between-group comparisons were performed at six timepoints (days 7 to 57) to evaluate inoculation with H. contortus To develop mathematical predictive models, CT versus IN comparisons at 7, 21, and 28 dpi were prioritized, as these timepoints revealed the highest number of significantly altered metabolites and the strongest diagnostic potential. For CT-D versus IN-D, predictive model development was prioritized at 35, 42, and 57 dpi to distinguish previously infected but now parasite-free animals from healthy controls. Analyzing the parasitology data Statistical analysis was conducted on the FEC data using R version 4.3.3 (R Core Team, 2024). Due to the non-normal distribution of FEC data 112 p Analyzing the metabolomic data Metabolomic datasets were pre-processed and normalized using standard methods available via MetaboAnalyst 6.0 113 114 p p For candidate biomarkers, significant ( p p 115 116 117 Pathway and enrichment analyses were performed for significant and candidate metabolites to identify their significant impact on metabolic pathways. The threshold for statistical significance reported in this study is a p p p Supplementary Information Below is the link to the electronic supplementary material.  Supplementary Material 1 Publisher’s note Springer Nature remains neutral with regard to jurisdictional claims in published maps and institutional affiliations. Acknowledgements The authors gratefully acknowledge the contributions of the research staff, Alison Neale, Emilie Edgar, and Lyndsey Smith, at the Technology Access Center for Livestock Production, as well as summer students Wing Hin Cheng and Jocelyn LeClaire from Olds College of Agriculture and Technology, Alberta, for their work on data collection. We also acknowledge the Center for Metabolomics Innovation, University of Alberta, for their support with metabolomics analysis. This project would not have been accomplished without the support of numerous personnel from the University of Calgary, the University of Alberta, Dalhousie University, and the funding agencies Results Driven Agriculture Research (RDAR), Mathematics of Information Technology and Complex Systems (MITACS), Ontario Sheep Farmers, Alberta Lamb Producers